Male. Sternite VIII emarginated at middle of posterior margin; sternite IX (
Fig. 27
) slightly emarginated medioapically; tergite X (
Fig. 28
) subtrapezoidal. Aedeagus (
Figs. 29, 30
) with median lobe distinctly asymmetrical and sharply pointed at apex, paramere symmetrical in apical half, as long as median lobe, underside of paramere (
Figs. 31–34
) with numerous sensory peg setae in apical portion.

Remarks.
The species may be readily recognized from all other species (except 

O. motuoensis


sp. n.

) by the metallic coloration and dense reticulation of the forebody. From 

O. motuoensis


sp. n.

described in this paper, it can be distinguished by the smaller body size (FL: 
6.7–7.1 mm
), the more rounded posterior angles of head (
Fig. 43
), the smaller ratio of TL/EYL (1.46–1.73), fewer large punctures on pronotum (
Fig. 43
), and the sparser punctation of abdominal tergites (
Fig. 45
).
